04386nam a22005535i 9780773552159DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2017434722  a97807735521597 a10.1515/97807735521592doi  a(DE-B1597)655147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aHD6300b.T46 2017 7aHIS0271702bisacsh04a331.6/266405672231 aThomas, Kevin J.A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContract Workers, Risk, and the War in Iraq :bSierra Leonean Labor Migrants at US Military Bases /cKevin J.A. Thomas. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHuman Dimensions in Foreign Policy, Military Studies, and Security Studies ;v500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Contract Workers, Recruiters, and International Migration -- tRisk and the Determinants of Labor Migration -- tSocial Transitions, Jobs, and Migration in Sierra Leone -- tRecruiting Workers and Preparing for Migration -- tSupporting the US Mission in Iraq -- tSupporting the US Mission in Iraq -- tReturn Migration, Reintegration, and “Blood Dollars” -- tMaking Migration Work -- tConclusion: Migration Systems, Risk, and the Future of Work -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2003, just before the start of the US invasion of Iraq, military planners predicted that the mission’s success would depend on using diverse sources for their workforce. While thousands of US troops were needed to secure victory in the field, large numbers of civilian contractors – many from poor countries in Africa and Asia – were recruited to provide a range of services for the occupying forces. In Contract Workers, Risk, and the War in Iraq Kevin Thomas provides a compelling account of the recruitment of Sierra Leonean workers and their reasons for embracing the risks of migration. In recent years US military bases have outsourced contracts for services to private military corporations who recruit and capitalize on cheaper low-skilled workers. Thomas argues that for people from post-conflict countries such as Sierra Leone, where there are high levels of poverty and acute unemployment, the opportunity to improve their situation outweighs the risk of migration to war-torn Iraq. Examining migrants’ experiences in their native country, at US bases, and after their return to Sierra Leone, Thomas deftly explores the intricate dynamics of risk, sets up a theoretical framework for future researchers, and offers policy recommendations for decision-makers and practitioners in the field. Incorporating the voices of Sierra Leonean contractors who were manipulated and exploited, Contract Workers, Risk, and the War in Iraq turns the spotlight on a subject that has remained on the periphery of history and reveals an unexpected consequence of the War on Terror.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aForeign workersxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aForeign workers, AfricanzIraq. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011. 0aMilitary bases, AmericanxGovernment policyzIraq. 0aSierra LeoneansxEconomic conditions. 0aSierra LeoneansxEmploymentzIraq. 0aSierra LeoneansxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Military / Iraq War (2003-2011).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773552159?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773552159423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773552159/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles